    "body": "As far as I understand this is the correct behaviour. The important thing here is the following: \"M\" refers to *end of month*. The following example will return \"M\":\r\n\r\n```python\r\nimport pandas as pd\r\npd.infer_freq(pd.to_datetime(pd.Series(['2018-10-31', '2018-11-30', '2018-12-31'])))\r\n\r\n```\r\n\r\nanother example that shows that your dates do not conform to freq = \"M\"  is\r\n\r\n```python\r\nimport pandas as pd\r\npd.DatetimeIndex([\"2018-10-03\", \"2018-11-03\", \"2018-12-03\"], freq=\"M\")\r\n\r\n```\r\n\r\nwhich will raise a ValueError! \r\n\r\nIf all you want is to check whether your dates are shifted by exactly a month, then you could do the following\r\n\r\n```python\r\nimport pandas as pd\r\nimport numpy as np\r\nt = pd.DatetimeIndex([\"2018-10-03\", \"2018-11-03\", \"2018-12-03\"])\r\noffset = pd.tseries.frequencies.to_offset(\"M\")\r\nmonth_end = t - offset   # timestamps at the end of the previous month\r\ndt = t - month_end  \r\nassert np.all(dt == dt[0])  # checks if the difference to the previous month end is the same for all entries\r\n\r\n```"
